ce:section.ce:para:
Cur, a natural compound that is considered in cancer therapy, was successfully conjugated onto the surface area of ZnFe2O4@mZnO-GQDs and ZnFe2O4@mZnO- N-GQDs nanocarriers. Therefore, drug delivery nano-carriers constructed via a non-covalent method are more desired. It was demonstrated that Cur could easily adsorb onto N-GQDs and GQDs via electrostatic interactions, strong π–π stacking, hydrogen-bonding and their combined action (shown in Scheme 4
                        ) [61]. The mesoporous ZnO creates a great accessible nanopore volume for loading of Cur molecules. Therefore, the large Cur storage could be attributed to the nanoporous surface of ZnO nano-layer (shown in Scheme 2). Specifically, the strategy of loading of Cur drug at the non-carrier sites is related to the ability of complexation of Cur with Zn2+ ions. This is extremely useful for drug releasing in acidic pH (5.5) and Cur–Zn complexes decomposition by external ultrasound radiation (shown in Scheme 2). The dissociation of Cur–Zn complex is due to protonation of the Cur drug at low pH (5.5) that caused the release of adsorbed Cur molecules into the target media [62]. As the cancer tumors have relatively low pH, therefore, this property is desirable for cancer treatment [62]. Compared with common nanocarriers, the Cur can be chemo-physical bonded to carbon of nano-materials via its aromatic moieties. Therefore the N-GQDs and N-GQDs nano-hybrid could be provide extremely high specific surface area, high drug loading content, good stability, pH-sensitive, US-sensitive, extendable, prolong able, sustainable release of anti-tumor drugs [63–65]. The Cur drug loading efficiency of ZnFe2O4@mZnO- N-GQDs nano-carrier increases with the nitrogen-doping of GQDs. The saturated drug loading efficiency can reach 76.45% and 64.71% w/w for ZnFe2O4@mZnO-N-GQDs and ZnFe2O4@mZnO-GQDs nanocarriers, respectively, the corresponding results are listed in Table 3
                        .
